description:
&lt;p&gt;An exciting opportunity has arisen for two Band 7 psychologists to join the SAFE (Supportive Action for Families in Ealing) Tier 2 CAMHS team. SAFE is a multi-agency service made up of social workers, family support workers, pupil and family workers, an educational psychologist and family safety worker who offer early help and support to families.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;CAMHS is embedded within this team, and CAMHS clinicians work closely with multi-agency colleagues to undertake joint assessment and intervention, and to offer consultation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The CAMHS team is comprised of clinical and counselling psychologists, assistant psychologists, family therapists, CBT therapists, Child Wellbeing Practitioners and nurses. The service offers evidence-based interventions, including CBT, family therapy, parenting work, and group work.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We support young people and families who present with a wide range of mental health difficulties, often in partnership with education and social care colleagues. We are currently considering new creative ways to meet the needs of our local families.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The post holders would provide a specialist psychology service to children and adolescents aged 0 -18 and their families; providing psychological assessment and therapy, and offering consultation on clients’ psychological care to non-psychologist colleagues within CAMHS, SAFE and the young people’s wider networks.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are opportunities to contribute to audit, service development and research, as well as build on supervision and consultation skills. Team members work autonomously within professional guidelines and within the overall framework of the team’s policies and procedures.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We have regular MDT meetings where we reflect on our clinical work. The post holders would be well supported in their role, with clear job plans, regular supervision, and opportunity to attend both local psychology meetings, and connect with the wider Ealing CAMHS and our trust-wide CAMHS colleagues.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We would welcome applications from innovative psychologists, including those newly qualified staff. We would also be interested in applications for those looking for part time hours.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please email Dr Nicola Meechan, Lead Clinical Psychologist, on nicola.meechan@westlondon.nhs.uk with any queries about the posts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We reserve the right to close adverts prior to the closing date stated should we receive a high volume of applications.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;All staff identified as at-risk and who meet the requirements of the post will be prioritised accordingly. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We will be requesting references. Please ensure you include email addresses and contact numbers for your referees which MUST be at supervisory or managerial capacity covering the last 3 years of employment to date, to avoid delay in the recruitment process. If your current/most recent organisation is an NHS trust, we will be requesting one reference from your current line manager/HR department.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We are keen to ensure that our workforce reflects the community it serves, particularly in terms of ethnicity, gender, disability and experience of mental illness.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;West London NHS Trust is committed to safeguarding all children and vulnerable adults and expects all staff and volunteers to share this commitment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further details / informal visits contact:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;NameDr Nicola MeechanJob titleLead Clinical PsychologistEmail addressnicola.meechan@westlondon.nhs.uk&lt;/p&gt;
